observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
a. demand the Municipal Treasurer to immediately deposit the undeposited balance totalling ₱93,519.17 from CY 2022 collections;
b. assign a new liquidating officer or an officer in charge in the receipt of cash remittances from the collectors and the deposit of the same in their respective fund accounts;
c. ensure that accountable officers in the Municipal Treasury Office report all collections to the accounting for recording and that remittances are deposited intact; and,
d. instruct the liquidating officer to provide a summary of the Report of Collection and Deposits (RCDs) already received by him/her in compliance with Section 62 of COA Circular No. 92-382 in order to ensure that all remittances received are reported and deposited intact.

We recommended and management agreed that the:

Municipal Accountant:

effect the proposed adjusting journal entries (Annex B, PAJE Nos.1-12) to establish the correct balances of affected accounts;

ensure that  all entries entering the trial balance are duly recorded in their respective journals and journal entry vouchers are supported with complete and appropriate documentation to support the adjusting journal entries made;

prepare, maintain the subsidiary ledgers of each account for easier monitoring and detection of errors, if any, and furnish copies to the Audit Team;

submit the supporting documents of the adjustment on the accounts Due to NGAs and Trust Liabilities – LDRRM made in the November 2020 trial balance under the Trust Fund.

Municipal Budget Officer prepare the List of Not Yet Due and Demandable Obligations (Annex E of COA Accounting Circular Letter 2007-002) at year-end which shall serve as a basis of the accounting department in booking up the obligations when they become due and demandable.

We recommended and management agreed that the:

Inventory Committee complete the inventory-taking pursuant to the guidelines set forth in COA Circular No. 2020-006;

Accounting and the property unit undertake collaborative procedures to reconcile the balances reflected in the RCPPE and the accounting records.

We recommended and management agreed that:

the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer use and maintain the RSMI using the form prescribed in Appendix 40 of the LGAM as basis in recording the issuance of inventories to end users and the recording of the related expense;

the Inventory Committee prepare either semi-annually or annually the RCPI using the form prescribed in Appendix 60 of the LGAM and submit a copy to the accounting and to the audit team not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively.

We recommended that:

The Municipal Engineering Office accelerate the conduct of pre-engineering activities to facilitate the publication and awarding of priority PPAs by the Bids and Awards Committee;

The Bids and Awards Committee consider the use of alternative modes of procurement when warranted to fast track the awarding of priority PPAs, thus ensuring timely completion and implementation of programmed programs/projects/activities (PPAs) as planned; 

Management ensure that the grant of time extension, suspension orders and variation orders are duly supported and for justifiable reasons only; 

The MDRRMO ensure that PPAs charged under the LDRRM fund will address the objectives and purpose of the fund.

We recommended that:

the Municipal Treasurer/General Services Officer maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; 




the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Accountant locate records of road networks in their offices where necessary data, specifications and locations of the Road Networks may be sourced to facilitate the recognition of road networks and the corresponding depreciation in the accounting books, the preparation of subsidiary ledgers and necessary disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended and management agreed that the:
Inventory Committee complete the inventory-taking pursuant to the guidelines set forth in COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Accounting and the property unit undertake collaborative procedures to reconcile the balances reflected in the RCPPE and the accounting records.

We recommended and management agreed that:
the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer use and maintain the RSMI using the form prescribed in Appendix 40 of the LGAM as basis in recording the issuance of inventories to end users and the recording of the related expense;
the Inventory Committee prepare either semi-annually or annually the RCPI using the form prescribed in Appendix 60 of the LGAM and submit a copy to the accounting and to the audit team not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Engineering Office accelerate the conduct of pre-engineering activities to facilitate the publication and awarding of priority PPAs by the Bids and Awards Committee;
The Bids and Awards Committee consider the use of alternative modes of procurement when warranted to fast track the awarding of priority PPAs, thus ensuring timely completion and implementation of programmed programs/projects/activities (PPAs) as planned;
Management ensure that the grant of time extension, suspension orders and variation orders are duly supported and for justifiable reasons only;
The MDRRMO ensure that PPAs charged under the LDRRM fund will address the objectives and purpose of the fund.
Management commented that the delays in implementation of projects were due to unworkable working conditions and restrictions caused by an upsurge of the virus which prevented access to main sources of construction materials. Copies of the approved suspension orders, time extensions related to the projects were submitted to the audit team after issuance of the AOM to justify the delays incurred.
The Bids and Awards Committee, on the other hand, commented that publication priority PPAs especially infrastructure projects depends on the availability of project cost estimates from the Municipal Engineering Office.
As for the LDRRM PPAs, the Municipal DRRM Officer informed the audit team that some of the delayed projects were suspended and some were extended due to change in some items to fit the requests and needs of the recipients, and inaccessibility due to location caused by unfavorable working conditions.
Nonetheless, management agreed to expeditiously publish, award and implement the priority programs and projects of the municipality and to work with the other concerned offices for proper monitoring.

We recommended that:

the Municipal Treasurer/General Services Officer maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; 

the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Accountant locate records of road networks in their offices where necessary data, specifications and locations of the Road Networks may be sourced to facilitate the recognition of road networks and the corresponding depreciation in the accounting books, the preparation of subsidiary ledgers and necessary disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements.

3.7	We recommended that:
3.7.1	the Municipal Treasurer/General Services Officer maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;
3.7.2	the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Accountant locate records of road networks in their offices where necessary data, specifications and locations of the Road Networks may be sourced to facilitate the recognition of road networks and the corresponding depreciation in the accounting books, the preparation of subsidiary ledgers and necessary disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

effect the proposed adjusting entries as provided in Annex F;

ensure timely submission of Bank Reconciliation Statements of funds maintained by the LGU;


furnish the audit team the corresponding subsidiary ledgers of accounts necessary to support their balances in the financial statements;

thoroughly review the accounting and reporting system of the LGU from the recording of transactions to the posting in the journals, preparation of the trial balance up to the financial statements to ensure the accuracy of account balances. 

We also recommended that the Supply Officer establish stock cards and conduct physical inventory at least once every semester and submit a Report of Physical Count of Inventories to the Accountant for necessary adjustment in the books.

We recommended that the:

General Services Officer in coordination with the MEO and the MPDO maintain  the Local Road Inventory, Road Map and Local Road Network Property Card to be updated every end of the accounting period;

Municipal Accountant maintain a Local Road Network Ledger Card  and update the costing of the Road Networks in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-008; 

Inventory Committee conduct annual inventory of roads and road components in compliance with DILG MC No. 2011-52.

We recommended that: 
management issue demand letters to all the debtors and exhaust all means to collect, otherwise, apply the collection of receivables to the co-makers;

the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer coordinate with the DSWD and Municipal Agriculture Office to adopt an efficient collection strategy to enforce collections from the concerned borrowers.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

instruct the Municipal Treasurer to deposit immediately the accumulated  collection of ₱1,778,251.10  as of December 31, 2014, otherwise, make further investigation on the reasons for its non-remittance and file an appropriate case, if warranted;



require the Municipal Treasurer to deposit intact all collections to the authorized depository bank pursuant to applicable rules and regulations for  the succeeding collections.

We have recommended that Management:

Instruct all accountable officers, officials and employees with cash advances that are due and demandable to submit their liquidation reports for proper accounting;

Exert all possible efforts to require the settlement of the outstanding cash advance from those resigned/separated officials and employees. If liquidation is not possible, request for write off of accounts receivable from the Commission Proper of the Commission on Audit.

Draft policies and guidelines on the rental of real properties by telephone companies and the use of the dormitory for approval by the SB; 

Determine the existing tenants of the buildings and execute contract of lease to the lessees, for the hiring of elf, ensure that a contract have been executed prior to the issuance of trip ticket for the vehicle ;

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to maintain index of payment for each lessee or tenant and to demand collection of unpaid rent; and 

In the preparation of official receipts, require the collectors to completely fill up the name of guests, number of days and inclusive dates of accommodation, applicable month and year of dormitory fees where applicable.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
effect the proposed adjusting entries as provided in Annex F;
ensure timely submission of Bank Reconciliation Statements of funds maintained by the LGU;
furnish the audit team the corresponding subsidiary ledgers of accounts necessary to support their balances in the financial statements;
thoroughly review the accounting and reporting system of the LGU from the recording of transactions to the posting in the journals, preparation of the trial balance up to the financial statements to ensure the accuracy of account balances.
We also recommended that the Supply Officer establish stock cards and conduct physical inventory at least once every semester and submit a Report of Physical Count of Inventories to the Accountant for necessary adjustment in the books.
The Municipal Accountant agreed to our recommendations.

We recommended that the:
General Services Officer in coordination with the MEO and the MPDO maintain  the Local Road Inventory, Road Map and Local Road Network Property Card to be updated every end of the accounting period;
Municipal Accountant maintain a Local Road Network Ledger Card  and update the costing of the Road Networks in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-008;
Inventory Committee conduct annual inventory of roads and road components in compliance with DILG MC No. 2011-52.

We recommended that management:
issue demand letters to all the debtors and exhaust all means to collect, otherwise, apply the collection of receivables to the co-makers;
the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer coordinate with the DSWD and Municipal Agriculture Office to adopt an efficient collection strategy to enforce collections from the concerned borrowers.

Investigate the recurring delayed remittances, issue memoranda to erring Revenue Collection Clerks and file administrative cases, if warranted; 

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to issue travel orders covering period of less than a week so that the RCCs still have time to remit their collections during Fridays and to constantly monitor their collections and remittances, and; 

Instruct all collectors to remit their collections daily to the LO/ Municipal Treasurer or if unavoidable as to the case of field collectors, remit collections on a weekly basis or as soon as collections have reached P 5,000.00  pursuant to applicable rules and regulations of the NGAS Manual to avoid exposure to theft or mishandling of funds.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor should:

instruct the Municipal Treasurer to deposit immediately the accumulated  collection of ₱1,778,251.10  as of December 31, 2014, otherwise, make further investigation on the reasons for its non-remittance and file an appropriate case, if warranted;



 require the Municipal Treasurer to deposit intact all collections to the authorized depository bank pursuant to applicable rules and regulations for  the succeeding collections.

We have recommended that:
the Municipal Accountant  strictly follow the Revised Chart of Accounts for LGUs in recording every transaction of the LGU;
the Municipal Administrator instruct concerned officials to submit regularly the report of inventory of supplies  and distributions or sale of inventory to the Office the Municipal Accountant for proper recording and adjustment in the books of the LGU.

We have recommended that Management:

require the BAC Secretariat to notify the observers 3 days prior to the procurement activity to enhance the transparency of the process;


require the BAC Secretariat to issue the standard form of the Philippine Bidding Documents to qualified bidders;


require the contractors to submit their bidders bond, bid securing declaration and performance securities in sufficient amounts to avoid disqualification of bids and suspension for a period of time from being qualified to participate in any government activity in case of violation of any of the conditions as required in the guidelines issued by the GPPB, and adhere to the provisions of Section 27 and 39 of the Revised IRR;


conduct post-qualification of the Lowest Calculated Bidder as required under Section 34.4 of RA 9184 to ensure that contracts are awarded to technically qualified and financially capable contractors; and


submit the lacking bid documents for immediate auditorial review; post the Notices of Award, Notices to Proceed and awarded contracts to the agency website and PhilGEPS, give justifications for the noted deficiencies; and henceforth, strictly comply with all the pertinent provisions of the RIRR of RA 9184.

We have recommended that Management:

instruct the Local School Board in the preparation of its Budget for the SEF, to prioritize programs and activities as stipulated in RA 5447, Section 272 of the Local Government Code and DECS-DBM-DILG Joint Circular Nos. 1; 


refrain from paying expenses not related or included in the list of priority expenses chargeable against SEF;

implement fully the programs, activities and projects identified in the LSB Budget in order to attain the objectives for the creation of the SEF;

adhere strictly to the rules and regulations on the utilization of the SEF as mandated by law.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

a. 	ensure that the 20% of the Internal Revenue Allotment be optimally utilized and fast track its implementation in order to achieve desirable socio-economic development and environmental outcome in compliance with the DILG DBM Joint Circular No. 2011-1;





evaluate the status of implementation of development projects and recommend the reversion of the unutilized funds for re-appropriation to other priority projects.
